<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; EQUIPMENT; PROFESSIONAL; DEATH; OBITUARY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Clarence Leo Fender, the electric guitar pioneer whose famous Stratocaster
model has been played by such rock stars as Buddy Holly, Eric Clapton and Jimi
Hendrix, has died. He was 82.;    Mr. Fender was found unconscious Thursday in
his home by his wife, Phyllis, and died en route to St. Jude Medical Center
and Rehabilitation Center, said police Sgt. Mike Maynard.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  C.L. FENDER, 82, PIONEER IN ELECTRIC GUITARS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Obituaries  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The death appeared to be from natural causes, Maynard said.;    Mr. Fender
had suffered from Parkinson's disease for decades but continued to work on
guitar designs at his shop.;    With its candy-colored curves, the
Stratocaster revolutionized music by making mass-produced electric guitars
that were affordable and had great sound.;    "He definitely was a pioneer.
It's still probably the No. 1 selling guitar in the world," said John
Carruthers, a guitar maker in Los Angeles who used to be a consultant to Mr.
Fender. "He was the Henry Ford of electric guitars. He basically turned it
into an assembly-line situation."  </TEXT>
