<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; PROFESSIONAL; PROFILE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IT'S HARD to say whether the times had more effect on Robert Cray, or Robert
Cray had more effect on the times -- at least as far as the blues world is
concerned.;    Remember the sensitive '70s, when Alan Alda was the role model
for insecure men who didn't know how to be polite to women who didn't want men
to open doors for them?  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Weekend  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE GUILTY BLUES OF ROBERT CRAY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     That's when the Robert Cray Band was formed -- in Eugene, Ore., in 1974 --
and over the years Cray has brought something new to the blues: neurotic,
angst-filled guilt.;    The theme was strongly heard on "Strong Persuader,"
his Grammy-winning 1986 album, especially on the hit "Right Next Door (Because
of Me)." That tune is like a zealot whipping himself, a man feeling bad about
breaking up his neighbor's marriage and a family over an extramarital affair.;
   It's heard again on Cray's latest album, "Midnight Stroll," in such tunes
as "My Problem": "I took all the love that I wanted / All I thought I needed /
To satisfy my selfish world." And on "Consequences": "I was smoking and
drinking and thinking when you walked by / The next thing I knew, I was making
up my alibi.";    These kinds of lyrics started showing up in his music, Cray
said during a recent phone interview from the North Bay, where he makes his
home, because he was trying to "figure out why something went wrong in a
relationship -- I do that, and so does everyone else I know who writes a song
-- and because, after a while playing clubs, some of the women yelled 'BS' at
the songs.;    "It's the male fashion (to accept guilt), as compared to the
blues in the past, where it was always the woman's fault -- not to say all the
songs are like that -- but nowadays you can be the one at fault. There's two
sides to every story.";    Cray, 37, also brought his own variation of the
blues sound to his guitar playing. About 1979 he picked up a Fender
Stratocaster with a thin, tinny tone that somehow fits his lyrics better than
the fat, rich sound of the Gibson he'd been playing.;    "I liked the sound,"
Cray said. "I picked one up, liked the way it felt. It's very accessible . . .
one volume control, two tones, easy to get to the (pick-up selection) switch.
Easy to play, fewer frets. Most Gibsons have 22, Strats have 21.";    As many
other blues players were going to a thicker tone -- such as Stevie Ray
Vaughan, who also played a Strat most of the time, but used thicker strings
and even Leslie organ speakers to get a richer sound -- or to a funkier beat,
such as Albert Collins, on his famous Telecaster, Cray continued to develop
his cleaner, cooler sound.;    And he's put it onstage with all of the blues
greats, from John Lee Hooker to Eric Clapton, who once jokingly threatened
Cray in a guitar showdown.;    "He said, 'Watch out, Cray, I'll cut you off at
the knees!' " Cray laughed as he recalled the jest. It happened at London's
Royal Albert Hall during a show that included one of Cray's other guitar
heroes, Buddy Guy, and pianist Johnnie Johnson, one of rock's founding fathers
and greatest players. "Clapton's mostly quiet and laid-back . . . he and Buddy
got into (trading guitar licks) onstage, but nobody's really out there trying
to cut anybody.";    The latest refinement of the Cray sound is the addition
of Memphis Horns, including trumpet player Wayne Jackson and sax player Andrew
Love, who were part of the rhythm-and-blues glory days at Stax records.;   
"They've had a big effect on the style," Cray said. "We're not really changing
the direction" of his rhythm and blues music, "but they changed the groove.
The material we're doing they fall into really good. It kind of broadened the
style of our music.";    Good-looking and tall (a Strat looks very small in
his hands), Cray sang "Brown-Eyed, Handsome Man" in the movie "Chuck Berry:
Hail! Hail! Rock 'n' Roll.";    He's made nine music videos in support of his
albums, and a collection of them was recently released to retailers. But Cray
said he feels a little uncomfortable about them.;    "They're fun sometimes,
but the whole thing about doing videos is not the reason we're in the band.
Some people see the videos only, don't see bands live, and that upsets me . .
. and it upsets me that you have to paint a picture of a song.";     Robert
Cray Band; With the Memphis Horns; Also: Otis Clay and Chicago Fire; Where:
The Warfield, 982 Market St., San Francisco; When: Tonight, Saturday; door at
8, show at 9; Tickets: $19-20, (415) 775-7722  </TEXT>
