<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: The Importance of Being a Gentleman</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's 11 a.m., an ungodly hour for most musicians
but just right for Eric Clapton _ a good time for cigarettes,
coffee and quiet conversation.
   He leans back in a green easy chair in his Manhattan hotel room,
his right ankle resting on the opposite knee. His face is deeply
tanned, the beard trim, his wavy brown hair brushed back. A black
T-shirt and bluejeans hang loosely from his rock star-skinny body.
   But it's the eyes you really notice _ the unwavering stare, how
the lids cut downwards at sharp angles, the way his brows form a
crease above his nose as he concentrates on what's being said and
considers his response.
   For a man who looks so reserved on stage, Clapton is in person,
surprisingly, a man of many words. He disapproves of asking
questions (bad manners, he says, observing is more his style), but
answers easily, spinning stories of the blues and the business.
   He talks about guitarists: early heroes such as Elmore James and
Buddy Guy, his all-time favorite; contemporaries, Jimi Hendrix and
Duane Allman; and young performers such as Robert Cray, a featured
player on Clapton's most recent album, ``Journeyman.''
   ``When you meet another guitarist, the first thing you do is
compare notes,'' Clapton, 45, explains. ``You find out who he
likes. `Do you like Robert Johnson?' It's a selfish kind of thing,
you always tend to like being around people who like the same
things you do.
   ``It was clear to me that Cray was a real dyed-in-the wool blues
musician. He's also very, very quiet, very aware, very sensitive.''
   There's a good example of the Clapton approach in the Chuck
Berry concert film, ``Hail! Hail! Rock 'n' Roll.'' Invited by
organizer Keith Richards, Clapton takes it slow, checking out
Berry, considering what he wants to sing. He eventually settles on
a rare Berry blues, ``Wee Wee Hours,'' and gives a typically
dignified performance.
   ``My attitude's always been to just tread carefully, be seen and
not heard,'' he says. ``When I used to see my heroes as a kid, I
would just watch and listen. It's the same thing when I got to know
them. Like Buddy Guy, I just watch him and I can see that he's
doing the same thing.
   ``He says every time he sees someone playing he learns
something, which is great.''
   For much of his career, Clapton has preferred to be heard and
not seen. He makes videos, but reluctantly, insisting he has no
interest in acting. Those eyes of an eagle were meant for checking
out other guitarists, not working cameras.
   In concert, he doesn't fall to his knees or bump and grind or
run from one end of the stage to the other when walking is so much
easier. It's just not dignified, not how a gentleman would behave.
   ``There's a line on the `Layla' album, `Do you want to see me
crawl across the floor to you?''' Clapton says, referring to ``Bell
Bottom Blues.''
   ``Some people could do that, crawl across the floor on stage. I
couldn't do that. I wouldn't be able to watch myself on TV if I
played like that. That would be embarrassing to me.''
   Clapton was born in 1945 in Ripley, a small town outside of
London. He became interested in music after seeing Jerry Lee Lewis
perform on television and received an acoustic guitar for his 14th
birthday.
   In the early 1960s, he began spending time in London
coffeehouses, listening to such England blues performers as Alexis
Korner, Cyril Davis and ``Long John'' Baldry. He joined his first
blues band, the Roosters, in 1963.
   Clapton earned a wide following in the mid-'60s with John
Mayall's Bluesbreakers and became an international star with Cream
toward the end of the decade.
   On originals such as ``Layla'' and ``I Can't Stand It,'' or
covers of Bobby Bland's ``Further on up the Road'' and Johnson's
``Ramblin' on My Mind,'' Clapton sings of gentlemen pushed to the
limit, down on the floor, their dignity tested by love, lies and
their own jealous hearts.
   ``Lately I've been running on faith. What else can a poor boy
do?'' he asks on ``Running on Faith'' from his ``Journeyman''
album. ``Sadness can't prevail,'' he sings on ``Pretending.''
``Everybody knows that strong love can't fail.''
   His greatest songs have been about despair and renewal, of
lonely years and the presence of the Lord, a walk with the devil's
music for a man who once inspired ``CLAPTON IS GOD'' graffiti on
walls around London.
   In 1970, the loss of faith pushed him to the extremes of
``Layla,'' with its five-alarm guitar riff and vocals that sound
like a man going down in flames.
   It pushed him to an anguished cover of Chuck Willis' ``It's too
Late.'' The original was gentle, the singer sadly resigned to
losing his girl. For Clapton, it's much worse. He's in tears, as if
life itself is slipping away, his fate confirmed by background
yells of ``Oh, she's gone!''
   Despair almost finished him in real life as well. ``Layla''
flopped when it was first released, and when he tried to record an
album with the same musicians the following year, the band fell
apart. Clapton developed a serious heroin addiction that forced him
into virtual seclusion for 2{ years.
   ``The most horrible I sound is when I've been burned out and in
a bad state of mind and bad state of health,'' Clapton says. ``You
have to live with it. If you can be happy with it when you're old,
you've got a much more contented life.''
   A gentleman, Clapton observed is a spiritual soul, and faith
regained brings out his more spiritual side. ``Let It Grow,'' from
his 1974 album ``461 Ocean Boulevard,'' sounds like one long sigh
of relief, an offer of thanks for his own survival. On ``Anything
for Your Love,'' off ``Journeyman,'' he sings of love as salvation,
his guitar lifting the song right off the ground.
   ``There's a yearning quality to it,'' he says, ``a spiritual
striving there that all musicians attain to. It's just inherent in
what you to, trying to achieve that which you couldn't really
achieve.''
   Muddy Waters, the great bluesman with whom Clapton became close
in the late 1970s, once spoke of the importance of being a
gentleman, and not the kind with a hat and cane: ``You don't have
to have a white face to be a gentleman and up to date with what
you're doing. You can be black, brown or any other color, but
you've got to carry yourself in a way that people know that you're
it.
   ``They might say I can't play or I can't sing, but, damn it,
they'll say I was a gentleman.''
   Clapton agreed, explaining the challenges of compressing a
lifetime of thoughts and feelings into five restless fingers.
   ``I think it has something to do with grace, being graceful in
your life as much as you can be. What happens is that no matter
what you play, it's a reflection of what you are.
   ``So if you live in a state of grace and dignity, it'll come out
in what you're playing. I'm starting to realize what I'm doing now
has to be good enough to be happy with in 20 years' time.''
</TEXT>
